      <h1>Five principles behind every technique</h1>
      <p class="concept-hero-subtitle">No matter the technique name, the foundation stays the same: entry, balance, direction, contact, and closure.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="news-meta">April 11, 2026</p>

    <p>
      In dojo practice, it is easy to get lost in labels: ikkyo, shihonage, iriminage, kotegaeshi.
      Techniques look different, but <strong>execution quality always rests on the same principles.</strong>
      Practitioners who understand them learn faster. Practitioners who ignore them collect variations without real progress.
    </p>

    <p>
      These principles are not theory for post-training discussion.
      They are operational criteria that immediately show whether a technique worked because it was truly built well,
      or because it was somehow forced through. Good dojos return to them constantly at every level.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Entry before force</h2>
    <p>
      If entry is late or shallow, the rest of the technique becomes damage control.
      First principle: position yourself so the technique starts from positional advantage,
      not from pushing. Ma-ai and timing matter more than tense shoulders.
    </p>

    <h2>2. Break balance, do not fight the person</h2>
    <p>
      Technique works when you take away stable alignment and guide structure.
      When you try to "win with strength," signs are obvious: movement gets heavy,
      elbows drift away from center, breath breaks. Kuzushi should be precise, not brutal.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Direction and continuity of movement</h2>
    <p>
      Every technique has a direction of guidance. If you keep changing vectors or stopping,
      the partner regains control. Third principle: from entry to finish, movement should carry one intent,
      without random pauses and without patched endings.
    </p>

    <h2>4. Contact and information reading</h2>
    <p>
      A good tori does not guess blindly. They read tension, resistance, rhythm change,
      and adjust in real time. Fourth principle: partner work is not mannequin work.
      Hand contact, body axis, and breath provide data that choreography memory cannot replace.
    </p>

    <h2>5. Closure and responsibility for outcome</h2>
    <p>
      Many practitioners lose quality at the end: after the throw they switch off awareness,
      or lose distance control. Fifth principle is zanshin and responsibility.
      A technique ends only when the situation is truly stable and safe—for both sides.
    </p>

    <h2>What absence of these principles looks like</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Too much force:</strong> the technique works only on weaker partners and collapses under resistance.</li>
      <li><strong>No structure:</strong> movement is fast but directionless and inconsistent in closure.</li>
      <li><strong>Repeat mistakes:</strong> the student knows names, but repeats the same technical gaps every week.</li>
      <li><strong>Selective listening:</strong> feedback is accepted only when it does not require changing a habit.</li>
      <li><strong>Demonstration over quality:</strong> technique is performed to look good, not to follow principle.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Seminar example: same shape, different quality</h2>
    <p>
      At seminars with a guest instructor, we often see the same pattern.
      A technique appears "familiar," but entry timing and direction emphasis differ from daily habit.
      Open practitioners re-check all five principles and adapt quickly.
      Closed practitioners keep reproducing old habits under new commentary and stall their development.
    </p>

    <h2>How to train the five principles consciously</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>One principle per round:</strong> focus one series on one criterion (e.g., entry only) instead of fixing everything at once.</li>
      <li><strong>Short correction loop:</strong> after feedback, do 2–3 immediate repetitions with one concrete change.</li>
      <li><strong>Partner rotation:</strong> test principles on different bodies and tempos to separate technique from familiarity.</li>
      <li><strong>Name error precisely:</strong> not "it failed," but "my entry was late" or "I lost direction after kuzushi."</li>
      <li><strong>Finish every technique:</strong> zanshin, distance, and readiness for continuation are part of execution, not extras.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      Different techniques teach different forms, but progress rests on the same foundation.
      These five principles—entry, balance, direction, contact, and closure—are a quality filter
      that works at every level. If you train through them consistently,
      technique becomes simpler, stronger, and more honest.
    </p>
